The key thing to understand is that LazyVerticalGrid has two built‑in ways to arrange items:
 • GridCells.Fixed(n) creates n columns that equally share the available width (so the size is dictated by parent dimensions), and
 • GridCells.Adaptive(minSize) creates as many columns as possible given a minimum cell width.

If you truly want grid cells that have a fixed size (say 100 dp) regardless of the overall width, you can use GridCells.Adaptive by passing your desired fixed size as the minimum size. For example:

 LazyVerticalGrid(
  cells = GridCells.Adaptive(minSize = 100.dp),
  contentPadding = PaddingValues(8.dp)
 ) {
  items(myItems) { item ->
   Box(
    modifier = Modifier
     .size(100.dp)
     .background(Color.LightGray),
    contentAlignment = Alignment.Center
   ) {
    Text(text = item.toString())
   }
  }
 }

Here’s what’s happening in this example:
 • GridCells.Adaptive(minSize = 100.dp) tells the grid “Use as many columns as you can while making sure that each cell is at least 100 dp wide.” (In many cases this causes each cell to be exactly 100 dp, but if there’s leftover space then the cells might expand a bit.) In contrast, if you used GridCells.Fixed(n) you would get exactly n columns whose widths are computed as the available space divided by n.
 • Additionally, wrapping your grid item content in a Modifier.size(100.dp) helps ensure that the content itself is fixed at 100 dp. (You may or may not need this depending on your layout requirements.)

In summary, when wanting cells with a fixed DP size using the deprecated LazyVerticalGrid, the recommended approach is to use GridCells.Adaptive with a given minSize. Note that LazyVerticalGrid has since been improved in later versions of Compose in the experimental LazyVerticalGrid API from androidx.compose.foundation.lazy.grid, which offers more control over cell sizing and spacing.

