Below is an example that demonstrates the proper way to use OrganizationServiceProxy to connect to a Dynamics CRM instance. In this example, you create the service’s URI, set up your client credentials (for example, with a username and password), instantiate OrganizationServiceProxy, and then use it as an IOrganizationService. Note that OrganizationServiceProxy implements IDisposable, so it’s best to use it within a using statement.

Example:

--------------------------------------------------
using System;
using System.ServiceModel.Description;
using Microsoft.Xrm.Sdk;
using Microsoft.Xrm.Sdk.Client;

class ConnectToCrm
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Replace with the URL of your Organization service.
        // This URL may vary depending on your CRM version and deployment configuration.
        Uri organizationUri = 
            new Uri("https://yourorg.crm.dynamics.com/XRMServices/2011/Organization.svc");

        // Set up credentials. For an on-premises instance you might use Windows credentials,
        // but for CRM Online you usually need ClientCredentials with username and password.
        ClientCredentials credentials = new ClientCredentials();
        credentials.UserName.UserName = "yourusername@yourorg.onmicrosoft.com";
        credentials.UserName.Password = "yourpassword";

        // Optionally, you can also pass in device credentials or other parameters. In this simple case
        // we are leaving those as null.
        // The second parameter is the home realm URI (which we set as null if not used).
        // The fourth parameter may include additional device credentials (often also null).
        using (OrganizationServiceProxy serviceProxy = 
               new OrganizationServiceProxy(organizationUri, null, credentials, null))
        {
            // Enable early-bound type support, if using early-bound entity classes generated by CrmSvcUtil.
            serviceProxy.EnableProxyTypes();

            // Now you have an instance of IOrganizationService to work with.
            // For example, you can retrieve information from CRM.
            Guid id = new Guid("some-valid-guid-for-an-entity-record");
            Entity account = serviceProxy.Retrieve("account", id, new Microsoft.Xrm.Sdk.Query.ColumnSet(true));

            Console.WriteLine("Retrieved {0} record with name: {1}",
                              account.LogicalName, account.Attributes["name"]);
        }
    }
}
--------------------------------------------------

Key Points:
1. Reference the appropriate assemblies: Microsoft.Xrm.Sdk and Microsoft.Xrm.Sdk.Client.
2. Set your Organization service URL correctly.
3. Use ClientCredentials with your CRM authentication details.
4. Use the using block to ensure the proxy is properly disposed.
5. Call EnableProxyTypes if you want to work with early-bound entity types.

This is the correct approach to connect to a Dynamics CRM instance using the OrganizationServiceProxy in C#.

