You can use the :nth-child(n) pseudo-class selector in CSS to target an element based on its position among its siblings. Here’s how it works:

• To select the third child element of a parent:
  element:nth-child(3) { 
    /* Your CSS here */ 
  }
For example, if you want to style the third list item in an unordered list:

  ul li:nth-child(3) {
    color: red;
  }

• You can also use keywords like odd or even:
  li:nth-child(odd) { 
    background-color: lightgray;
  }

• And you can use formulas to target a pattern of elements:
  p:nth-child(2n) { 
    /* This selects every even paragraph */
  }

A few points to remember:
1. The counting starts from 1.
2. The selector matches the element only if it is the nth child of its parent (regardless of type). If you need to select based on type (e.g., the third paragraph among other paragraphs), consider using :nth-of-type.

That's how you select the nth-child element in CSS!

