Rofi is highly customizable, and its appearance can be tailored by applying custom themes and configuration settings. Here are the main ways to customize menus in Rofi:

1. Theme Files (Rasi Files):
 • Rofi uses theme files written in its own “rasi” syntax. These files control colors, fonts, border styles, and layout of menus.
 • You can create your own theme file (for example, theme.rasi) with custom definitions. For instance, you might specify:

   /* theme.rasi */
   window {
    background: "#282a36";
    border: "#bd93f9";
    border-radius: 5px;
   }
   listview {
    columns: 1;
   }
   element {
    padding: 5px;
    border-radius: 3px;
    spacing: 2px;
   }
   textbox {
    text-color: "#f8f8f2";
    font: "monospace 10";
   }

 • To use this theme, invoke Rofi with the command-line option:
   rofi -show run -theme path/to/theme.rasi

2. User Configuration File:
 • Rofi also reads a configuration file usually found at ~/.config/rofi/config.rasi or ~/.config/rofi/config.
 • You can include theme definitions or import themes there. For example, you might have:
   @import "path/to/theme.rasi"
 This lets you centralize your settings so that every Rofi invocation uses your custom style.

3. Command-Line Options:
 • In addition to theme files, you can control some appearance settings directly via command-line options when launching Rofi. For instance, you might change font or colors like so:
   rofi -show run -font "monospace 10" -bw 2
 (where “-bw” sets the border width).

4. Overriding specific elements:
 • Within your theme file, you can override specific elements or widgets. Rofi themes generally use sections like window, listview, element, and textbox. Consult the Rofi documentation or sample theme files (available in the Rofi GitHub repository) for the full list of configurable properties.
 • For example, you can style the prompt, the selected element, or even individual elements with different states (hover, active, etc.).

5. Testing and Iteration:
 • It’s common to tweak and reload your theme until it meets your needs. You can keep one terminal open to test Rofi changes, then modify your theme file while re-invoking Rofi.

By combining these methods, you can control nearly every aspect of how Rofi’s menus appear and behave. For more details and property listings, refer to the official Rofi documentation or sample themes which provide a wealth of examples to build on.

