JavaScript doesn't have a built-in method to determine whether a number is prime. Instead, developers typically implement their own function—most commonly using the trial division method. The basic idea is to check whether the number has any divisors other than 1 and itself. Here’s an example implementation using trial division:

------------------------------------------------------------
function isPrime(n) {
  // Handle edge cases:
  if (n <= 1) return false; // 0 and 1 (and negative numbers) are not prime
  if (n <= 3) return true;  // 2 and 3 are prime numbers

  // Eliminate even numbers and multiples of 3 quickly:
  if (n % 2 === 0 || n % 3 === 0) return false;

  // Only test potential factors up to the square root of n.
  // Using the 6k ± 1 optimization (because all primes greater than 3 
  // are of the form 6k ± 1) to check fewer numbers.
  for (let i = 5; i * i <= n; i += 6) {
    if (n % i === 0 || n % (i + 2) === 0) return false;
  }

  return true;
}

// Example usage:
console.log(isPrime(17)); // true
console.log(isPrime(18)); // false
------------------------------------------------------------

How It Works:
1. The function first handles small numbers and edge cases.
2. It quickly excludes even numbers and multiples of 3 (after checking 2 and 3 directly).
3. Then it iterates from 5 up to the square root of n, checking factors of the form 6k - 1 and 6k + 1.
4. If any divisor is found, the function returns false; otherwise, it returns true once the loop completes.

This is one of the most common approaches to determine if a number is prime in JavaScript. For very large numbers, more advanced algorithms (like the Miller-Rabin primality test) might be more efficient, but trial division is sufficient for many common scenarios.

