In React, you handle form submissions using the onSubmit event. Within your event handler, you typically call event.preventDefault() to prevent the default behavior (such as the page reloading when a form is submitted).

For example:

--------------------------------------------------
import React from 'react';

function MyForm() {
  const handleSubmit = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent the default form submission behavior
    // Your submission logic here
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type="text" name="example" />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}

export default MyForm;
--------------------------------------------------

In this example, React’s onSubmit event triggers the handleSubmit function, where event.preventDefault() stops the browser’s default action of reloading the page.

