In Java, swapping two elements in an array is usually done by using a temporary variable to hold one of the values during the swap. For example, consider you have an array arr and you want to swap arr[i] and arr[j]. The swap would be performed like this:

  int temp = arr[i];
  arr[i] = arr[j];
  arr[j] = temp;

This operation ensures that the value from arr[i] isn’t lost when you overwrite arr[i] with arr[j]. This simple swap is often used in algorithms that move non-zero elements to the start of an array (or perform other in-place reordering) by exchanging elements as needed.

