You can use composite literals to initialize nested struct fields—even if those fields contain complex types like slices, maps, or other structs. Composite literals let you build up the entire data structure in one go, which is especially handy in unit tests.

For example, suppose you have the following types:

-------------------------------------------------
type Inner struct {
    Values  []int
    Details map[string]string
}

type Outer struct {
    Field1 int
    Data   Inner
}
-------------------------------------------------

In your test, you can initialize an Outer value (including a properly initialized Inner value) like this:

-------------------------------------------------
testValue := Outer{
    Field1: 42,
    Data: Inner{
        Values: []int{1, 2, 3},
        Details: map[string]string{
            "key1": "value1",
            "key2": "value2",
        },
    },
}
-------------------------------------------------

This approach directly assigns the nested struct (Inner) as a composite literal inside the outer struct (Outer). You can nest as deeply as you need—even if your nested struct fields include slices, maps, or other structs.

If your nested structs include pointers or optional fields, you can also initialize those appropriately. For instance, if you had:

-------------------------------------------------
type Inner struct {
    Values  *[]int
    Details *map[string]string
}
-------------------------------------------------

In your test, you might write:

-------------------------------------------------
values := []int{1, 2, 3}
details := map[string]string{
    "key1": "value1",
    "key2": "value2",
}

testValue := Outer{
    Field1: 42,
    Data: Inner{
        Values:  &values,
        Details: &details,
    },
}
-------------------------------------------------

Using composite literals this way keeps your test data setup concise and readable.

