Since .NET Core 2.1, the recommended approach is to use IHttpClientFactory. Here’s why and how:

• IHttpClientFactory creates HttpClient instances that share a pooled and managed underlying HttpMessageHandler. This setup automatically handles DNS changes by periodically refreshing the handler, mitigating stale DNS issues.

• It also prevents socket exhaustion by reusing HttpMessageHandler instances rather than creating new ones for each HttpClient. Creating a new HttpClient per request without proper disposal can lead to exhaustion of the sockets.

• IHttpClientFactory supports named clients and typed clients, which can be configured with policies (like timeouts or retries) and message handlers tailored to your needs.

To use it, register it in your Startup.cs (or Program.cs for newer project templates):

  services.AddHttpClient();

Then inject the HttpClient wherever needed:

  public class MyService
  {
      private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

      public MyService(HttpClient httpClient)
      {
          _httpClient = httpClient;
      }

      // Use _httpClient to make HTTP calls
  }

Or use named client for more specific configuration:

  services.AddHttpClient("MyClient", client =>
  {
      client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com/");
  });

And inject it like so:

  public class MyService
  {
      private readonly IHttpClientFactory _clientFactory;

      public MyService(IHttpClientFactory clientFactory)
      {
          _clientFactory = clientFactory;
      }

      public async Task GetDataAsync()
      {
          var client = _clientFactory.CreateClient("MyClient");
          var response = await client.GetAsync("resource");
          // handle response
      }
  }

By using IHttpClientFactory, you ensure that your application manages connections efficiently, avoids socket exhaustion, and adapts to DNS changes appropriately without the need for manual socket handler management.

