Unreal Engine provides an HTTP module that you can use in your C++ projects to perform HTTP requests. Specifically, you work with the FHttpModule, which is part of the HTTP module. When using it, you'll typically include headers such as "HttpModule.h", "IHttpRequest.h", and "IHttpResponse.h". Remember to add "HTTP" as a dependency in your project’s Build.cs file under Public or Private dependencies.

For example, in your Build.cs file, you might have:

PublicDependencyModuleNames.AddRange(new string[] { "Core", "CoreUObject", "Engine", "HTTP" });

Then in your C++ code you can access the HTTP module as follows:

--------------------------------------------------
#include "HttpModule.h"
#include "Interfaces/IHttpRequest.h"
#include "Interfaces/IHttpResponse.h"

void MyClass::SendRequest()
{
    FHttpModule* Http = &FHttpModule::Get();
    TSharedRef<IHttpRequest, ESPMode::ThreadSafe> Request = Http->CreateRequest();

    Request->OnProcessRequestComplete().BindUObject(this, &MyClass::OnResponseReceived);
    Request->SetURL("http://example.com/api");
    Request->SetVerb("GET");
    Request->ProcessRequest();
}

void MyClass::OnResponseReceived(FHttpRequestPtr Request, FHttpResponsePtr Response, bool bWasSuccessful)
{
    if (bWasSuccessful && Response.IsValid())
    {
        // Process the response
    }
}
--------------------------------------------------

This module provides all the necessary functionality to work with HTTP requests within Unreal Engine.

